## Data-analysis policies (R stack)

Base rigor for reproducible, auditable analysis. Each lives under `analysis/`.
Open only the one the task needs.

| Policy                                | One-line scope                                                      |
|---------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `analysis/numeric-computation.md`     | Numbers are claims — compute by code/tool, never in your head       |
| `analysis/data-protection.md`         | Data stays local; nothing identifiable leaves unless you ask  |
| `analysis/data-integrity.md`          | Raw immutable; verify join cardinality; explicit types; range checks|
| `analysis/data-contracts.md`          | Validate raw + analysis-ready data at the gates; block on failure   |
| `analysis/data-onboarding.md`         | Copy light / connect heavy data; portable config; minimal human docs|
| `analysis/pre-specification.md`       | Define estimand/outcome before seeing results; flag post-hoc        |
| `analysis/initial-data-analysis.md`   | Structured IDA before modeling (STRATOS); distinct from EDA         |
| `analysis/missingness.md`             | Account for every row; mechanism-aware handling; no silent deletion |
| `analysis/outliers.md`                | Detect→inspect→document; never silent removal; sensitivity          |
| `analysis/model-assumptions.md`       | Graphics over tests; right residual per model; a violation ≠ invalid           |
| `analysis/sensitivity-analysis.md`    | Pre-specify; reuse the pipeline; report alongside the primary       |
| `analysis/reproducibility.md`         | Seeds via targets; renv.lock committed; locale/TZ; sessioninfo; stamp|
| `analysis/regenerables.md`            | Only input+code to git; everything regenerates; `make reset`        |
| `analysis/computational-efficiency.md`| Vectorize; data.table/DuckDB by size; cache/freeze long runs        |
| `analysis/reporting.md`               | Labels-first; always CIs; no p in comparison tables (STROBE); rounding      |
| `analysis/results-writing.md`         | Objective; every number & data-dependent word via inline code       |
| `analysis/figures.md`                 | Colorblind-safe palettes; grayscale test; vector + ≥300 dpi; journal sizes |
| `analysis/diagrams.md`                | flowchart (sketch-first) for results; mermaid + ISO 5807 for process|
| `analysis/methods-documentation.md`   | Write methods continuously; LaTeX notation registry; supplement     |
| `analysis/pseudocode-first.md`        | Pseudocode in its own file → validate → code → test                 |
| `analysis/incremental-functions.md`   | Abstract only when scaling; demo without→with; STOP-and-confirm gate |
| `analysis/code-style.md`              | Tutorial-readable analysis code; comment the why; tests apart       |

### Precedence within the analysis layer

Truth and safety first; the constitution and `anti-hallucination.md` still outrank
everything below:

```
numeric-computation  >  data-protection  >  data-integrity / data-contracts / data-onboarding
  >  (methodology: pre-specification, initial-data-analysis, missingness, outliers,
      model-assumptions, sensitivity-analysis)
  >  reproducibility / regenerables / computational-efficiency
  >  (reporting: reporting, results-writing, figures, diagrams)
  >  (workflow: methods-documentation, pseudocode-first, incremental-functions, code-style)
```

Slash / parenthesis groups are co-equal stages that rarely conflict — order them
by workflow, not by rank. **Across layers:** the constitution outranks the
universal precedence, which outranks this analysis-layer precedence. When the
`health-data` profile adds policies, they carry their own precedence and overlay
this chain. Most of these never conflict; when they do, stop and name the trade-off.
